{"key":"post-9713317","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9713317</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;muse said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I thought misting pins was bad, that it might cause aborts.&amp;nbsp; I'm almost certain I have read this many times in these forums. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You have read that.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It's because several years ago, the knowledge of the mushroom growing life cycle was not as evolved as it is now.&amp;nbsp; That bad advice was circulating when people thought that the best way to build a terrarium was to seal it up tight.&amp;nbsp; If you have an air-tight terrarium, and you mist, there's nowhere for that moisture to go, so the pins drown.&amp;nbsp; If you're providing the proper amount of fresh air, your pins will benefit from misting, and in fact they require it.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Since air exchange is the number 1 pinning trigger, you MUST mist or your substrate will dry out.&amp;nbsp; It's amazing how many new growers build a perfectly good fruiting chamber, and then bitch that it won't 'maintain humidity'.&amp;nbsp; When prodded for information, the story comes out that they're not misting. &lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/shrug.gif&quot; alt=&quot;:shrug:&quot; title=&quot;:shrug:&quot;/&gt;&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9713388</next>\n<prev>9713281</prev>\n<first>9711812</first>\n<last>9716272</last>\n<when>1233450015</when>\n<utime>02/01/09 03:00 AM</utime>\n</post>"}